Each created being is distinct from others, and so has a distinct intelligibility; the Divine Essence cannot by itself be identical with all these different objects. As one seal stamps only one species ol impression, so God must have other patterns besides His Essence to stamp the multitude ol creatores with (ib, l. 28, 293 p. 7, l. 1—35). 1t is absurd to say that an Infinite Artist requires no model for His creations. On the contrary, the greater the artist, the more perfect his mental pattern is (p. 8, l. 7-15). Only in the case of a finite artist the mental pattern is not eternal; with the Infinite Artist, it is eternal or is not at all (ib, l. 15-38). The distinctness of God’s knowledge of all things in Himsell implies a mul- titude of ideas; il there were only a lew, or one, the knowledge would be confused. And what of God's knowledge ol things that never were, nor will be, but only might be? The object ol that knowledge must be in Himsell, or not exist at all. We must therefore admit an Ideal World, if we admit that anything can exist (p. 9, l. 1-60).

Note by the way that Wyclil here openly admits the possibility of things that never are nor will be. As we have shown elsewhere, this is in conflict with this more matured system. He had not yet extended his conclusion to every possible particular being; but the drift of his argument was already leading him that way.
